solutions.content:
# Intuition
We try to interleave `s1` & `s2` in every possible way that can form string `s3`. We can use recursion to explore all possible ways & find if there exist an answer for any possibility.

# Recursion
Let's define a recursive boolean function `canInterleave`. where, `canInterleave(k, i, j)` tells us that is it possible to interleave `s1[i...end]` & `s2[j...end]` to form `s3[k...end]`.
Therefore our answer will be `canInterleave(0, 0, 0)`.

## Code
```
class Solution {
    bool canInterleave(int k, int i, int j, string& s1, string& s2, string& s3) {

        // All indices reached the end then interleaving is possible
        if(i == s1.length() && j == s2.length() && k == s3.length())
            return true;

        // Intially considering that interleaving is not possible
        bool res = false;

        // Check if we can match s1[i] to s3[k]
        // and if we can, can we get answer by matching them
        if(i < s1.length() && s1[i] == s3[k])
            res |= canInterleave(k + 1, i + 1, j, s1, s2, s3);

        // Check if we can match s2[j] to s3[k]
        // and if we can, can we get answer by matching them
        if(j < s2.length() && s2[j] == s3[k])
            res |= canInterleave(k + 1, i, j + 1, s1, s2, s3);

        return res;
    }

public:
    bool isInterleave(string s1, string s2, string s3) {
        return canInterleave(0, 0, 0, s1, s2, s3);
    }
};
```

## Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(2^{len3})$$, where `len3` is length of string`s3`.
Because at a hypothetical situation, we'll have 2 possibilities for every character in `s3` that either match it with character in `s1` or in `s2`.

- Space complexity:
$$O(len3)$$, Because the recursion depth will be at most `len3` & every function call will have its constant space.

# Memoization
Above solution will not work because of it's exponential nature. but we can optimize by memoizing it as there will be overlapping subproblems which we evaluate again & again unnecessarily.

## Code
```
class Solution {
    bool canInterleave(int k, int i, int j, string& s1, string& s2, string& s3, vector<vector<vector<int>>>& dp) {

        // All indices reached the end then interleaving is possible
        if(i == s1.length() && j == s2.length() && k == s3.length())
            return true;

        if(dp[k][i][j] != -1)
            return dp[k][i][j];

        // Intially considering that interleaving is not possible
        bool res = false;

        // Check if we can match s1[i] to s3[k]
        // and if we can, can we get answer by matching them
        if(i < s1.length() && s1[i] == s3[k])
            res |= canInterleave(k + 1, i + 1, j, s1, s2, s3, dp);

        // Check if we can match s2[j] to s3[k]
        // and if we can, can we get answer by matching them
        if(j < s2.length() && s2[j] == s3[k])
            res |= canInterleave(k + 1, i, j + 1, s1, s2, s3, dp);

        return dp[k][i][j] = res;
    }

public:
    bool isInterleave(string s1, string s2, string s3) {
        int len1 = s1.length(), len2 = s2.length(), len3 = s3.length();
        vector dp(len3 + 1, vector<vector<int>>(len1 + 1, vector<int>(len2 + 1, -1)));
        return canInterleave(0, 0, 0, s1, s2, s3, dp);
    }
};
```

## Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(len1*len2*len3)$$, Because there are `len1*len2*len3` dp states to evaluate.

- Space complexity:
$$O(len3) + O(len1*len2*len3)$$, For recursion stack space & dp array respectively.

# Tabulation
We can eliminate recursion stack space from previous solution by using a bottom up tabulation solution as follows

## Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isInterleave(string s1, string s2, string s3) {
        int len1 = s1.length(), len2 = s2.length(), len3 = s3.length();
        vector dp(len3 + 1, vector<vector<int>>(len1 + 1, vector<int>(len2 + 1, false)));

        dp[len3][len1][len2] = true;

        for(int k = len3 - 1; k >= 0; k--) {
            for(int i = len1; i >= 0; i--) {
                for(int j = len2; j >= 0; j--) {
                    bool res = false;
                    if(i < len1 && s1[i] == s3[k])
                        res |= dp[k + 1][i + 1][j];

                    if(j < len2 && s2[j] == s3[k])
                        res |= dp[k + 1][i][j + 1];

                    dp[k][i][j] = res;
                }
            }
        }

        return dp[0][0][0];
    }
};
```

## Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(len1*len2*len3)$$, Because there are `len1*len2*len3` dp states to evaluate.

- Space complexity:
$$O(len1*len2*len3)$$, For dp array.

# Space Optimization
To calculate dp states for any index `k` we do not need all the previously calculated states we just need dp states for index `k+1`. We can use this to eliminate the 3D dp array with just 2 2D dp arrays.

## Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isInterleave(string s1, string s2, string s3) {
        int len1 = s1.length(), len2 = s2.length(), len3 = s3.length();
        vector curdp(len1 + 1, vector<bool>(len2 + 1, false));
        vector nextdp(len1 + 1, vector<bool>(len2 + 1, false));

        nextdp[len1][len2] = true;

        for(int k = len3 - 1; k >= 0; k--) {
            for(int i = len1; i >= 0; i--) {
                for(int j = len2; j >= 0; j--) {
                    bool res = false;
                    if(i < len1 && s1[i] == s3[k])
                        res |= nextdp[i + 1][j];

                    if(j < len2 && s2[j] == s3[k])
                        res |= nextdp[i][j + 1];

                    curdp[i][j] = res;
                }
            }
            nextdp = curdp;
        }

        return nextdp[0][0];
    }
};
```

## Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(len1*len2*len3)$$, Because there are `len1*len2*len3` dp states to evaluate.

- Space complexity:
$$O(len1*len2)$$, For dp array.

